{"title_page": "Pamela S. Karlan", "text_new": "{{short description|American legal scholar}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Pamela Karlan\n| image = Pamela S. Karlan (49565892516) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Karlan at the [[Edmond J. Safra Center for Ethics]] in 2020\n| birth_name = Pamela Susan Karlan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|1|1}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| education = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| occupation = American legal scholar\n| years_active = 1984\u2013present\n| partner = [[Viola Canales]]\n}}\n'''Pamela Susan Karlan''' (born February 1, 1959) is an American professor of law at [[Stanford Law School]]. A leading legal scholar on [[Voting rights in the United States|voting rights]] and political process, she served as U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for Voting Rights in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Division]] from 2014 to 2015.<ref>{{ cite news | last = Taylor | first = Stuart | title = An excellent Supreme Court shortlist | work = National Journal | publisher = [[Atlantic Media|Atlantic Media Company]] | url = http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100412025442/http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | archivedate = 2010-04-12 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nKarlan earned her B.A. degree in history from [[Yale University]] in 1980, as well as an M.A. degree in history and [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1984.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | title = Profile: Pamela S. Karlan | url = http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | publisher = Stanford Law School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080605222907/http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | archivedate = 2008-06-05 }}</ref> At [[Yale Law School]], she served as an article and book reviews editor of the ''[[Yale Law Journal]]''.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web | last = Karlan | first = Pamela S. | title = CV | url = https://www-cdn.law.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2015.KarlanCV.December1.pdf |accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation from law school, Karlan worked as a [[law clerk]] for former U.S. District Judge [[Abraham David Sofaer]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] from 1984 to 1985. She went on to clerk for [[U.S. Supreme Court Justice]] [[Harry Blackmun]] the following year. In a 1995 oral history with [[Harold Koh]], Blackmun revealed that his dissent in ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]'' had been written primarily by Karlan. He said that Karlan \"did a lot of very effective writing, and I owe a lot to her and her ability in getting that dissent out. She felt very strongly about it, and I think is correct in her approach to it. I think the dissent is correct.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Volokh | first = Eugene | title = Saturday, April 23, 2005 | publisher = The Volokh Conspiracy: The Washington Post | date = 23 April 2005 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | url = http://volokh.com/archives/archive_2005_04_17-2005_04_23.shtml#1114025448 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter her clerkships, Karlan worked as an assistant counsel at the [[NAACP]] [[NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund|Legal Defense and Educational Fund]] from 1986 to 1988.\n\nFrom 1988 to 1998, Karlan taught law at the [[University of Virginia]] [[University of Virginia School of Law|School of Law]], where she won the All-University Outstanding Teaching Award in 1995\u201396 and the [[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia]]'s Outstanding Faculty Award in 1997.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In 1998, Karlan joined the faculty of [[Stanford Law School]]. She is the school's Kenneth and Harle Montgomery Professor of [[Public interest law|Public Interest Law]]. In 2004, Karlan cofounded the Stanford Supreme Court Litigation [[Legal clinic|Clinic]], through which students litigate live cases before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"cv\" /> In 2002, Karlan won the school's prestigious John Bingham Hurlbut Award for Excellence in Teaching.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nKarlan has frequently commented on legal matters for ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''. During the disputed [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 presidential election]], she appeared regularly in the news media to discuss its comportment with constitutional law. In the aftermath of the election, Karlan, [[Samuel Issacharoff]], and [[Richard Pildes]] adapted two chapters from the law school casebook that they co-authored into a book entitled, ''When Elections Go Bad: The Law of Democracy and the Presidential Election of 2000''.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn December 4, 2019, Karlan\u2014alongside law professors [[Noah Feldman]], [[Michael Gerhardt]], and [[Jonathan Turley]]\u2014testified before the House Judiciary Committee regarding the constitutional grounds for presidential impeachment in the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|Impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"2019 - New York Times - Who Is\">{{cite news |last1=Fadulu |first1=Lola |title=Who Is Pamela Karlan? Legal Leader Committed to Progressive Causes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/us/politics/pamela-karlan.html |work=The New York Times |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> She made a controversial statement delivered during the December 2019, impeachment hearing of President Trump, \u201cContrary to what President Trump has said, Article 2 [of the Constitution] does not give him the power to do anything he wants,\u201d testified Pamela Karlan, a professor at Stanford Law School. \u201cThe Constitution says there can be no titles of nobility, so while the president can name his son Barron, he can\u2019t make him a baron.\u201d Karlan apologized afterward. <ref>C-Span: Professor Pamela Karlan references Barron Trump and later apologizes for it. Dec 4, 2019. </ref>  \n\nKarlan is a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Appellate Lawyers]], and the [[American Law Institute]].<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n=== Public service ===\nIn 2003, she was appointed to the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]] by [[California State Controller|Controller]] [[Steve Westly]]. Until 2005, she served as commissioner to help implement and enforce [[California]]\u2019s [[Campaign finance in the United States|campaign finance]], [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]], and [[conflict of interest]] laws.<ref name=\"cv\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2013, Karlan was appointed by the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to serve as the U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for [[Voting rights in the United States|Voting Rights]] in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Gerstein | first = Josh | title = Karlan to take Justice Department voting rights post | url = http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2013/12/karlan-to-take-justice-department-voting-rights-post-180045.html?hp=l10 | date = 20 December 2013 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | work = [[Politico|The Politico]] | publisher = Capitol News Company }}</ref> The position did not require confirmation by the [[U.S. Senate]]. Karlan took up her post on January 13, 2014, and served for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?pamelakarlan|title=Pamela S. Karlan {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Gregg | first = Remington | title = HRC Blog: Pamela Karlan takes helm as Deputy Assistant Attorney General in DOJ Civil Rights Division | website = hrc.org | publisher = Human Rights Campaign | url = http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/pamela-karlan-take-helm-as-deputy-assistant-attorney-general-in-doj-civil-r | date = 13 January 2014 | accessdate = 23 March 2014 }}</ref> For her work in implementing the Supreme Court decision in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', she received the Attorney General\u2019s Award for Exceptional Service, the DOJ's highest award for employee performance.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Pamela S. Karlan Biography|url=https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/|website=Stanford Law School|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her career, Karlan has been an advocate before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Adam |last= Liptak | title = So, guy walks up to the bar, and Scalia says... | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/31/politics/31mirth.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 31 December 2005 }}</ref> She was mentioned as [[Barack Obama Supreme Court candidates|a potential candidate]] to replace Supreme Court Justice [[David Souter]] when he retired in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | title = Articles about Pamela S. Karlan | work = [[The New York Times]] | url = http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/k/pamela_s_karlan/index.html  }}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nPeter Baker, a New York Times political writer, described the subject as \"a full-throated, unapologetic liberal torchbearer\".<ref>Baker, Peter. (25 May 2009). \"Favorites of Left Don\u2019t Make Obama\u2019s Court List\". [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/26/us/politics/26court.html New York Times website] Retrieved 1 February 2020.</ref>  Karlan has said that the United States should help Ukraine fight Russia so that the United States does not have to fight Russia on its own territory.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tim |last= Hains | title = Professor Karlan: Ukraine Is Important \"So We Can Fight The Russians There And We Don't Have To Fight Them Here\" | url = https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/12/04/professor_karlan_ukraine_is_important_so_we_can_fight_the_russians_there_and_we_dont_have_to_fight_them_here.html | work = [[RealClearPolitics]] | date = 4 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKarlan told ''[[The Politico|Politico]]'' in 2009, \"It's no secret at all that I'm counted among the [[LGBT]] crowd\".<ref name=polico_20090505>{{cite news |first=Josh |last=Gerstein | work = [[The Politico]] |url= http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0509/22106.html |title=Groups push for first gay Supreme Court justice |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 | publisher = Capitol News Company}}</ref> She has described herself as an example of \"snarky, [[bisexual]], Jewish women\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/expertforum/stanford-law-professor-pam-karlan-concludes-2006-acs-national-convention/|title=American Constitution Society Blog: Stanford Law Professor Pam Karlan concludes 2006 ACS National Convention|last=|first=|date=22 June 2006|website=|publisher=American Constitution Society for Law and Policy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref> Her partner is writer [[Viola Canales]].<ref>{{cite news  |first= Esselink |last= Jean Ann | title = On our radar \u2013 An overdue thank you To Pamela Karlan | work = The New Civil Rights Movement | url = http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/on-our-radar-an-overdue-thank-you-to-pamela-karlan/news/2013/12/29/80872 | date = 29 December 2013 | accessdate =23 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n==Works and publications==\n===Selected books===\n* {{cite book |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=A Constitution for All Times |date=2013 |publisher=MIT Press |location=Cambridge, MA |isbn=978-0-262-01989-7 |oclc=863038741|jstor=j.ctt9qf8bs }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Issacharoff |first1=Samuel |last2=Karlan |first2=Pamela S. |last3=Pildes |first3=Richard H. |last4=Persily |first4=Nathan |title=The Law of Democracy: Legal Structure of the Political Process |date=2016 |publisher=Foundation Pres |location=St. Paul, MN |isbn=9781628102253 |edition=5th |url=http://www.thelawofdemocracy.com/ |oclc=956640376}}\n\n===Selected journals===\n* {{cite journal |last1=Brennan |first1=William J. |last2=Ginsburg |first2=Ruth Bader |last3=Arnold |first3=Richard S. |last4=Griswold |first4=Erwin N. |last5=Karlan |first5=Pamela S. |last6=Koh |first6=Harold Hongju |title=A Tribute to Justice Harry A. Blackmun |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=1994 |volume=108 |issue=1 |pages=163\u20138 |issn=0017-811X |jstor=1341989|pmid=3333213 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=The Supreme Court \u2013 Comments. Electing Judges, Judging Elections, and the Lessons of Caperton |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=November 2009 |volume=123 |issue=1 |pages=80\u2013103 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/karlan09.pdf |issn=0017-811X |oclc=472051099}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=Henry J. Miller Lecture Series: Old Reasons, New Reasons, No Reasons |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Summer 2011 |volume=27 |issue=4 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol27/iss4/2/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=8092032473}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=In Memoriam: William J. Stuntz |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=June 2011 |volume=124 |issue=8 |pages=1841\u20131843 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/vol124_stuntz_tribute.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=The Swing Justice: Reflections on the Career of Justice Anthony Kennedy. Panel 1: Abortion and Gay Rights |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Spring 2019 |volume=35 |issue=5 (Supplement) |pages=871\u2013905 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol35/iss5/1/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=1101178994}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/ Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Stanford University Law School]]\n* {{C-SPAN|Pamela Karlan}}\n* [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=136810 Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Social Science Research Network]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karlan, Pamela S.}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bisexual academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American legal scholar}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Pamela Karlan\n| birth_name = Pamela Susan Karlan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|1|1}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| education = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| occupation = American legal scholar\n| years_active = 1984\u2013present\n| partner = [[Viola Canales]]\n}}\n'''Pamela Susan Karlan''' (born February 1, 1959) is an American professor of law at [[Stanford Law School]]. A leading legal scholar on [[Voting rights in the United States|voting rights]] and political process, she served as U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for Voting Rights in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Division]] from 2014 to 2015.<ref>{{ cite news | last = Taylor | first = Stuart | title = An excellent Supreme Court shortlist | work = National Journal | publisher = [[Atlantic Media|Atlantic Media Company]] | url = http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100412025442/http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | archivedate = 2010-04-12 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nKarlan earned her B.A. degree in history from [[Yale University]] in 1980, as well as an M.A. degree in history and [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1984.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | title = Profile: Pamela S. Karlan | url = http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | publisher = Stanford Law School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080605222907/http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | archivedate = 2008-06-05 }}</ref> At [[Yale Law School]], she served as an article and book reviews editor of the ''[[Yale Law Journal]]''.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web | last = Karlan | first = Pamela S. | title = CV | url = https://www-cdn.law.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2015.KarlanCV.December1.pdf |accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation from law school, Karlan worked as a [[law clerk]] for former U.S. District Judge [[Abraham David Sofaer]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] from 1984 to 1985. She went on to clerk for [[U.S. Supreme Court Justice]] [[Harry Blackmun]] the following year. In a 1995 oral history with [[Harold Koh]], Blackmun revealed that his dissent in ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]'' had been written primarily by Karlan. He said that Karlan \"did a lot of very effective writing, and I owe a lot to her and her ability in getting that dissent out. She felt very strongly about it, and I think is correct in her approach to it. I think the dissent is correct.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Volokh | first = Eugene | title = Saturday, April 23, 2005 | publisher = The Volokh Conspiracy: The Washington Post | date = 23 April 2005 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | url = http://volokh.com/archives/archive_2005_04_17-2005_04_23.shtml#1114025448 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter her clerkships, Karlan worked as an assistant counsel at the [[NAACP]] [[NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund|Legal Defense and Educational Fund]] from 1986 to 1988.\n\nFrom 1988 to 1998, Karlan taught law at the [[University of Virginia]] [[University of Virginia School of Law|School of Law]], where she won the All-University Outstanding Teaching Award in 1995\u201396 and the [[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia]]'s Outstanding Faculty Award in 1997.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In 1998, Karlan joined the faculty of [[Stanford Law School]]. She is the school's Kenneth and Harle Montgomery Professor of [[Public interest law|Public Interest Law]]. In 2004, Karlan cofounded the Stanford Supreme Court Litigation [[Legal clinic|Clinic]], through which students litigate live cases before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"cv\" /> In 2002, Karlan won the school's prestigious John Bingham Hurlbut Award for Excellence in Teaching.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nKarlan has frequently commented on legal matters for ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''. During the disputed [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 presidential election]], she appeared regularly in the news media to discuss its comportment with constitutional law. In the aftermath of the election, Karlan, [[Samuel Issacharoff]], and [[Richard Pildes]] adapted two chapters from the law school casebook that they co-authored into a book entitled, ''When Elections Go Bad: The Law of Democracy and the Presidential Election of 2000''.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn December 4, 2019, Karlan\u2014alongside law professors [[Noah Feldman]], [[Michael Gerhardt]], and [[Jonathan Turley]]\u2014testified before the House Judiciary Committee regarding the constitutional grounds for presidential impeachment in the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|Impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"2019 - New York Times - Who Is\">{{cite news |last1=Fadulu |first1=Lola |title=Who Is Pamela Karlan? Legal Leader Committed to Progressive Causes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/us/politics/pamela-karlan.html |work=The New York Times |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> She made a controversial statement delivered during the December 2019, impeachment hearing of President Trump, \u201cContrary to what President Trump has said, Article 2 [of the Constitution] does not give him the power to do anything he wants,\u201d testified Pamela Karlan, a professor at Stanford Law School. \u201cThe Constitution says there can be no titles of nobility, so while the president can name his son Barron, he can\u2019t make him a baron.\u201d Karlan apologized afterward. <ref>C-Span: Professor Pamela Karlan references Barron Trump and later apologizes for it. Dec 4, 2019. </ref>  \n\nKarlan is a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Appellate Lawyers]], and the [[American Law Institute]].<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n=== Public service ===\nIn 2003, she was appointed to the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]] by [[California State Controller|Controller]] [[Steve Westly]]. Until 2005, she served as commissioner to help implement and enforce [[California]]\u2019s [[Campaign finance in the United States|campaign finance]], [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]], and [[conflict of interest]] laws.<ref name=\"cv\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2013, Karlan was appointed by the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to serve as the U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for [[Voting rights in the United States|Voting Rights]] in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Gerstein | first = Josh | title = Karlan to take Justice Department voting rights post | url = http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2013/12/karlan-to-take-justice-department-voting-rights-post-180045.html?hp=l10 | date = 20 December 2013 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | work = [[Politico|The Politico]] | publisher = Capitol News Company }}</ref> The position did not require confirmation by the [[U.S. Senate]]. Karlan took up her post on January 13, 2014, and served for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?pamelakarlan|title=Pamela S. Karlan {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Gregg | first = Remington | title = HRC Blog: Pamela Karlan takes helm as Deputy Assistant Attorney General in DOJ Civil Rights Division | website = hrc.org | publisher = Human Rights Campaign | url = http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/pamela-karlan-take-helm-as-deputy-assistant-attorney-general-in-doj-civil-r | date = 13 January 2014 | accessdate = 23 March 2014 }}</ref> For her work in implementing the Supreme Court decision in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', she received the Attorney General\u2019s Award for Exceptional Service, the DOJ's highest award for employee performance.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Pamela S. Karlan Biography|url=https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/|website=Stanford Law School|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her career, Karlan has been an advocate before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Adam |last= Liptak | title = So, guy walks up to the bar, and Scalia says... | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/31/politics/31mirth.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 31 December 2005 }}</ref> She was mentioned as [[Barack Obama Supreme Court candidates|a potential candidate]] to replace Supreme Court Justice [[David Souter]] when he retired in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | title = Articles about Pamela S. Karlan | work = [[The New York Times]] | url = http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/k/pamela_s_karlan/index.html  }}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nPeter Baker, a New York Times political writer, described the subject as \"a full-throated, unapologetic liberal torchbearer\".<ref>Baker, Peter. (25 May 2009). \"Favorites of Left Don\u2019t Make Obama\u2019s Court List\". [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/26/us/politics/26court.html New York Times website] Retrieved 1 February 2020.</ref>  Karlan has said that the United States should help Ukraine fight Russia so that the United States does not have to fight Russia on its own territory.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tim |last= Hains | title = Professor Karlan: Ukraine Is Important \"So We Can Fight The Russians There And We Don't Have To Fight Them Here\" | url = https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/12/04/professor_karlan_ukraine_is_important_so_we_can_fight_the_russians_there_and_we_dont_have_to_fight_them_here.html | work = [[RealClearPolitics]] | date = 4 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKarlan told ''[[The Politico|Politico]]'' in 2009, \"It's no secret at all that I'm counted among the [[LGBT]] crowd\".<ref name=polico_20090505>{{cite news |first=Josh |last=Gerstein | work = [[The Politico]] |url= http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0509/22106.html |title=Groups push for first gay Supreme Court justice |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 | publisher = Capitol News Company}}</ref> She has described herself as an example of \"snarky, [[bisexual]], Jewish women\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/expertforum/stanford-law-professor-pam-karlan-concludes-2006-acs-national-convention/|title=American Constitution Society Blog: Stanford Law Professor Pam Karlan concludes 2006 ACS National Convention|last=|first=|date=22 June 2006|website=|publisher=American Constitution Society for Law and Policy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref> Her partner is writer [[Viola Canales]].<ref>{{cite news  |first= Esselink |last= Jean Ann | title = On our radar \u2013 An overdue thank you To Pamela Karlan | work = The New Civil Rights Movement | url = http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/on-our-radar-an-overdue-thank-you-to-pamela-karlan/news/2013/12/29/80872 | date = 29 December 2013 | accessdate =23 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n==Works and publications==\n===Selected books===\n* {{cite book |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=A Constitution for All Times |date=2013 |publisher=MIT Press |location=Cambridge, MA |isbn=978-0-262-01989-7 |oclc=863038741|jstor=j.ctt9qf8bs }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Issacharoff |first1=Samuel |last2=Karlan |first2=Pamela S. |last3=Pildes |first3=Richard H. |last4=Persily |first4=Nathan |title=The Law of Democracy: Legal Structure of the Political Process |date=2016 |publisher=Foundation Pres |location=St. Paul, MN |isbn=9781628102253 |edition=5th |url=http://www.thelawofdemocracy.com/ |oclc=956640376}}\n\n===Selected journals===\n* {{cite journal |last1=Brennan |first1=William J. |last2=Ginsburg |first2=Ruth Bader |last3=Arnold |first3=Richard S. |last4=Griswold |first4=Erwin N. |last5=Karlan |first5=Pamela S. |last6=Koh |first6=Harold Hongju |title=A Tribute to Justice Harry A. Blackmun |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=1994 |volume=108 |issue=1 |pages=163\u20138 |issn=0017-811X |jstor=1341989|pmid=3333213 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=The Supreme Court \u2013 Comments. Electing Judges, Judging Elections, and the Lessons of Caperton |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=November 2009 |volume=123 |issue=1 |pages=80\u2013103 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/karlan09.pdf |issn=0017-811X |oclc=472051099}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=Henry J. Miller Lecture Series: Old Reasons, New Reasons, No Reasons |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Summer 2011 |volume=27 |issue=4 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol27/iss4/2/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=8092032473}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=In Memoriam: William J. Stuntz |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=June 2011 |volume=124 |issue=8 |pages=1841\u20131843 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/vol124_stuntz_tribute.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=The Swing Justice: Reflections on the Career of Justice Anthony Kennedy. Panel 1: Abortion and Gay Rights |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Spring 2019 |volume=35 |issue=5 (Supplement) |pages=871\u2013905 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol35/iss5/1/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=1101178994}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/ Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Stanford University Law School]]\n* {{C-SPAN|Pamela Karlan}}\n* [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=136810 Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Social Science Research Network]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karlan, Pamela S.}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bisexual academics]]\n", "name_user": "Poldavia", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pamela_S._Karlan"}
